<br>
For exp groups all should be equal. One of the three just offers different options and benefits to the group. On raids I think there should be different encounters designed for each class to tank as well. But all three could substitute in but one tank class would have the tools to do it just a tad better than the others. That in my opinion is actual balance.<br>
<br>
I still believe that DPS is an issue to a point.  I don't think any tank should outdamage a wizard but if you close the gap just enough that smart well balanced group play produces the highest exp rate versus knights chain casting aggro spells against casters going off the wall it will make the game more enjoyable for all three classes.  <br>
Right now my DPS doesn't matter one bit.  I've done whole missions and exp groups doing nothing but casting one spell and no one ever noticed a difference in kill rate. This is wrong.  <br>
I wish they would have implemented our Terror spells decently and actually make them worth using.  If they'd fix those so they would be useable and would give us a decent amount of agro but nothing like CD or Fear and make it so people can't sit there and chain nuke to their heart's content I'd be much happier overall.<br>
<br>
Malagis, If you're talking about truely high end knight gear there are sacrfices to be made where some of those elemental focus items are what we're stuck with instead of the superior stats from time gear.  Just because I choose not to play in that level of the game doesn't mean I don't take a peek at the armors from time to time.  If magelo is stable at some point, not working for me now, I'll add a &quot;hell frozen over&quot; profile to my magelo which is how I'd gear a SK with focus effects, FT and the likes.<br>
<br>
I do agree that in the high level game the gap closes too much.  Right now our longest raiding warriors in my guild have a quite sizeable lead in HP over me(1.3 and 1.5k) and I feel we're fairly well balanced towards each other in that respect. But at my point in the game the HP difference actually means something.  A 1k HP difference at the time stage doesn't mean as much as it does for me now. <br>
<br>
Which is another problem. How do you make a sizeable enough HP gap that doesn't trivialize content worse than a knight being able to tank it? Personally, I think a quick fix would be give Warriors PE 2 and 3 that would follow the arch type percentage levels. This would also help them reinforce their mitigation and avoidance further over knight classes.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The 80% 'rule' is so funny, we should reverse it and give warriors 80% of a knights utility, or even go with 95% of a knights utility to compensate for the 95% tanking ability compared to a warrior. Thats where the imbalance lies, knights have 95% of a warriors tanking ability and HP's and they get oogles of 'utility' to compensate for the miniscule differences while warriors gain nothing but that whopping 5% edge.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Warriors', and all pure melee for that matter, big problem is lack of utility. You won't ever catch me denying that. I agree with a lot of what you said. Defensive has royally messed up any shot at tanking balance for a very long time now.  With it they can't upgrade you too much. Without it they can actually fix the class and not make it revolve around 3 minutes of glory. Defensive bends us over the table just as much as it does to you.<br>
